Jahrelang war Koks eines der heißumstrittensten und begehrtesten Exportgüter der Ruhr. Heute werden gegenüber dem Vorjahre monatlich fast hunderttausend Tonnen weniger exportiert.

Weniger Stahl bedeutet also Einschränkung der Kokserzeugung. Weniger Koks aber ist gleichzusetzen mit einem geringeren Gasanfall. An dieser Konjunkturverwandtschaft würde es deshalb liegen, wenn den westdeutschen Hausfrauen im Falle eines kommenden strengen Winters jemand auf den Gasschlauch treten sollte. Auch für die Großchemie und die eisenschaffenden Betriebe wäre eine Wiedereinführung des Gaszuteilungs-Systems und der Gasabschaltungen ein schwerer Rückschlag.

Daß es nicht soweit kommt, erhofft sich die Ruhrindustrie von einer Hilfe aus dem Bonner Wirtschaftsministerium.

Besprechungen mit Professor Erhard sollen bald nach seinem Wieder-Amtsantritt zu irgendeiner Entlastung der Überproduktion an Koks führen. Der bisher ventilierte Vorschlag einer direkten 200 - Millionen - Mark - Subvention für die Lagerung ist fallengelassen zugunsten koksverschlingenden Schienen - Auftrages einer etwaigen Vorfinanzierung eines der Bundesbahn.

posts.com: Monolid is a cold weather adaption. It decreases the risk of snow blindness. It developed somewhere around eastern siberia and north china. In non-snow areas with monolids they result from people from the north migrating southwards. It's just 1 genetic trait though. You can have 1% ancestry from a monolid population and still have a small chance of getting a monolid, at the same time you can be 99% mongol and still not have a monolid. Most finns don't have them, I would guess around 5% of them maybe from what I have observed myself. You can't really gauge the amount of admixture from just this trait. This works for most traits. You can find blondes in afghanistan sometimes, this doesn't mean they are more european than the others, its just that afghanistan has a small greek admixture from ancient time so sometimes it just pops up randomly.

Przykłady:

1. To matki i babcie od dziecka nam wmawiają, że jesteśmy przystojni i w ogóle jacy zajebiści, żadna osoba płci męskiej z rodziny czegoś takiego nie mówi. Potem idziesz do szkoły/na uczelnia/do pracy i zero zainteresowania, patrzysz w lustro, ryj krzywy, no ale przecież babcia powiedziała.


2. Wiecie jaki jest idealny wzrost dla mężczyzny według kobiet? Poniżej 180. Nie wierzycie? Ja też, ale tak wychodzi w badaniach, gdzie pyta się kobiety o ich opinie na temat idealnego wzrostu. Z czego to wynika? A no właśnie z braku szczerości, nawet w anonimowych badaniach potrzeba udowadniania sobie i innym, że wcale się nie leci na wysokich facetów jest tak silna, że się w takich ankietach kłamie.


3. Podobnie z kwestią wyglądu. Mamy trzy wartości: wygląd, pieniądze, charakter. Mężczyźni i kobiety muszą ułożyć je według własnych priorytetów, po czym sprawdza się na podstawie speed datingu i związku jak to wygląda w praktyce.

Jak to wygląda po sprawdzeniu empirycznie? Faceci najbardziej sobie cenią: 1. Wygląd 2. Osobowość 3. Pieniądze
Wszystko się zgadza.
Co deklarują kobiety? 1. Osobowość 2. Pieniądze 3. Wygląd.
Jak się sprawa ma po sprawdzeniu? 1. WYGLĄD 2. Osobowość 3. Pieniądze
Czyli klasyczne robienie z siebie księżniczki, która "nie patrzy na wygląd tylko wnętrze", a później brutalna weryfikcja, że to bzdury. Okłamywanie siebie i innych w anonimowym badaniu XD

Sasa,

Naona unaendelea vizuri.
You've been adopting Kiswahili to your vocabulary (Posters, boyfriend, anniversary, matchmakers), similar to what I do. Almost all users of Kiswahili, at least in Kenya, are multilingual. At the initial phases they borrow a lot of the vocabulary from their main or other languages. Eventually you'll build your Kiswahili vocabulary but you'll still keep borrowing words due to its limited vocabulary. Everyone's Kiswahili is unique as a result of this. I'm curious as to what your version will turn out to be. Probably similar to the one I use, "Sheng" (Kiswahili Grammar + English vocabulary + Some slang words)

>Kati
The view from the top of the hill is quite romantic
Maoni = View (Opinion meaning)
There is no Kiswahili for "view" as used in the above context.
The only way to translate it is through paraphrasing the original information
View juu ya mlima huwa romantic
>The view at the top of the hill is romantic
The paraphrased English sentence has some grammar mistake (replacing from with at) but if you use it to translate to Kiswahili, it makes sense.

Always remember Kiswahili belongs to no one. You make it your own. My grandfather's Kiswahili is different from mine. It is meant to be a simple language that you pick up quickly in order to interact with people from different backgrounds. The message is more important than the cosmetic aspects of it(accent, vocabulary, etc.) It's what English is today with less steps.

Hopefully one day you meet someone from the Coastal parts of Kenya (Mombasa, Malindi,etc) Tanzania or Zanzibar if you seek the pure fancy version.

>Ich [bin mir] sicher, dass ich [vor (dem) Ende des/dieses Jahres] eine Freundin bekommen werde.
'I feel sure' seems a bit weird in English too; just translate literally here
reordered the adverbial so it's more standard, but not strictly incorrect yours
>Viele Poster/Pfostierende in /lang/ würden einen Freund [vor einer] Freundin bevorzugen.
you'd want to make clear if it refers to a more than a platonic friend. the English sentence strictly doesn't have to, but I think it's strongly implied.
dict says
etw./jmdn. (vor/gegenüber etw./jmdm.) bevorzugen - to prefer sth./so. (over/to sth./so.)
jmdn. (vor/gegenüber jmdm.) bevorzugen - to favour/privilege so. (over/to so.)
the extended forms including the brackets are a bit unwieldy, so with this verb you can save on the preposition (but only if you're secure in your cases):
>Viele Poster in /lang/ würden einen [festen Freund / Partner] einer [feste Freundin / Partnerin] vorziehen. - Many posters in /lang/ would prefer a boyfriend to a girlfriend.
probably more common in speech:
>Viele Poster in /lang/ hätten lieber einen [festen Freund / Partner] als eine [feste Freundin / Partnerin]. - Many posters in /lang/ would rather have a boyfriend than a girlfriend.

>>176517264
Oh, Polish has spodobovanie too? Seems to works slightly differently, than in Slovak (voicing follows the last letter of the cluster + there are some rules about clusters across word boundaries), but yeah, people sometimes make mistakes. You learn where voicing/devoicing happens and to try to use different inflections when unsure about spelling. In practice you just know how words are written (do you sound out wed-nes-day in your head when writing it?), but it might be hard for kids, especially when there are no inflections to use. Slovak kids tend to confuse the prepositions "s" with "z" and the male plural genitive suffix -ov with the female singular instumental suffix -ou. We also had a tiny spelling reform in the 50s that changed words like smluva and sväz to zmluva and zväz to closee match pronunciation.

>assimil
I went through 32 lessons of Assimil French with Ease. I can't recommend the method. If it was 1998, I would have said it was the best book for French available. With how things are now, I can't say that anymore. The book isn't inherently comprehensible. It requires you to read through the translations for each sentence that you don't understand. This would have been super useful, because the only alternative I would have had was flipping through the pages of a physical French-English dictionary. The ability to get instant definitions like this in the 90s would have been amazing. The problem is that hover dictionaries exist now, so instant definitions to whatever I want is always there.
The other problem I have with Assimil French with Ease is that it's dated. It tries to prepare you for a vacation in 90s Paris. A lot of the vocabulary is totally useless (random food items, occupations, and formal speech that I'll never actually read in media).
In my opinion, you're better off reading something like French subtitles for different TV shows like an Irish anon mentioned earlier.
The only thing I would use Assimil for is for languages that don't have much resources available to begin with.

>>176518470
Assimil is only meant to be the beginning of one's studies. The virtue of Assimil is that it provides you a sizable chunk of the language which you're supposed to repeat into oblivion and once you have it internalized you will have a solid and long lasting foundation in the language. The problem with what you suggest is that it's really difficult without having a foundation in the language — just what Assimil gives. Plus, repetition is better for drilling the new structures and vocab into your head that a wave of input at first. Trust me, I've used Assimil for half a dozen languages now and can't recommend it more highly. I probably own close to 20 of their books for numerous languages. If I had to relearn French, I would use Assimil, not using the pure input method you suggest which I indeed used.
Also, if you're concerned about "outdated" vocab, you can use the newer editions. Though the old ones are superior imo.

>mnatumia alot of english words
Since Kenya has a lot of unique communities, Kiswahili used to be our common language. After independence, English joined Kiswahili as a formal language. English progressively started replacing Kiswahili as a medium for a lot things (medium if learning the moment you join nursery school, medium of interacting with the world outside Kenya, any formal interaction, etc.) As more people went to school, the more English took over Kiswahili. The thing that Kiswahili has going for it is its simplicity, the syntax is simple. So the current version is as I mentioned Kiswahili syntax + Basic kiswahili vocabulary (eat/kula, lala/sleep) + Engkish vocabulary (Mainly nouns and verbs) + Slang (If you're from Nairobi).
Initially I wanted to help you with this version of Kiswahili since I believe it is the easiest since the emphasis is on Kiswahili's syntax. Use the vocabulary you already have (English) to practise and master the syntax. Later as you advance, all you need is place the English vocabulary. Just master the pronouns, tenses and syntax. However, I found your Kiswahili too formal and I assumed you mainly wanted that, which is nice. I tried to help you with that. I still believe you should try "Sheng", the hybrid Kiswahili I mentioned earlier. It'll help you master the basics. You still have to learn the basic survival vocabulary. You're sort of only allowed to replace " advanced/uncommon " words with the equivalent.
I'll try and come up with examples that show why the hybrid one is used. It is sort of efficient and simplifies Kiswahili and English
>Are you coming?
Una-come
>Mwanakandarasi
Contractor
>Did you call call him?
Ulim-call?
>He already submitted the statements.
Asha-submit statements

All you need is a actual real time practice.

Yeah, it does strange even to me at times especially when trying to explain to someone such as you. Once you get the hang of it, you realise it is about looking for the syllables in verbs.
>Asha-submit
A - He/she (pronouns have no gender in Kiswahili)
Sha - has already
Submit - submitted (the sha already implies past tense. Verbs do not change in Kiswahili. You simply add a syllable before it to indicate time (the tense). Learn the syllable and you've mastered the tenses of every verb.

He/she has already submitted
Asha-submit

>>176524011
>most of the time its quite tedious, which is why I just use Tue English words time to time
See, you finally get it. Mostly people already know other languages. Their community's/tribal language is more important. Nobody wants to be arsed (excuse my kiswahili) to learn the full vocabulary and whichever new Kiswahili words get invented to keep up with the times. What mist people want are the basics so that they can interact with others. It is more if a social language. If you need more, you revert your main language, use English or learn theirs (or they learn yours).

In may be wrong but I do not think Tanzania or Zanzibar is as diverse as we are. So Kiswahili is sort of the only language that they have. In Kenya most people know at least three (Tribe, Kiswahili, English). Interact with another community and you add to your portfolio.
We still learn the pure one in school until high school but still mostly override it with the hybrid one, sheng
The Coastal version (Malindi, Kenya, Lamu, etc) is similar to the Tanzanian or Zanzibar version. The way I would put it is that our Version is similar to Americanised English while their Kiswahili is still the Old school British, Sherlock Holmes sort of English.
You'll definitely understand them. It genuinely does sound nicer, more pure. I believe it's mostly as result of it being their main or only language. You cannuae sheng to get the basics (pronouns, propositions, tenses,,,) and eventually upgrade to it. The syntax is similar. The main difference is the vocabulary and accent.
